  <feedback condition="$correct">$correctFeedback</feedback>
  <feedback condition="$multiplied">The <ref uri="https://open.lib.umn.edu/algebra/chapter/6-1-the-logarithm-function/">logarithm function</ref> returns the exponent that the base must be <em>raised to</em> that results in the input argument, <m>$c{simplify}</m>. It looks like you took the product of <m>$a</m> and <m>$c{simplify}</m>, which is not the correct operation.</feedback>
  <feedback condition="$c = 1 and $ans1.creditAchieved != 1 and $ans1.responseHasBeenSubmitted">It's a good time to review your <ref uri="https://open.lib.umn.edu/algebra/chapter/topic-6-2-solving-a-linear-equation-in-one-variable/">properties of logarithms</ref>.
<p>Recall, that any number raised to the <m>0^{th}</m> power is equal to <m>1</m>, so for any <m>a</m>, 
    <me>a^0 = 1.</me></p>
    <p>Now, applying this fact to the logarithm function, we have that the logarithm function, evaluated at <m>1</m> for any base <m>a</m> must be equal to <m>0</m>,
      <me>\log_a 1 = 0 \;\;\text{implies}\;\;a^0 = 1</me></p>
  </feedback>

    <feedback condition="$ans1.numSubmissions > 2 and $ans1.creditAchieved != 1">
      <p>The definition of the <ref uri="https://open.lib.umn.edu/algebra/chapter/6-1-the-logarithm-function/">logarithm function</ref> is:
  <me>\log_a x = y \;\;\text{implies}\;\;a^y = x</me>
where <m>a >0, a \neq 1</m> and <m> x > 0</m>. The first step when computing the logarithm without a calculator is to rewrite the equation in exponential form. Then, ask yourself, "what exponent must <m>a</m> be <em>raised to</em> to result in <m>x</m>?" The answer to this question is the exponent <m>y</m>.</p>
    </feedback>
  



<!--*********************************************
            Hint
**********************************************-->
<hint name="helpSection"><title>Worked Example</title>

  
<p>Here is a similar worked example:</p> 
<example>
<p><em>Find <m>\log_{12} 144</m></em></p> 

<p><em><alert>Solution.</alert></em></p>
    <md>
      <mrow>\log_a x \amp= y \;\;\text{implies}\;\;a^y = x \amp\text{general definition}</mrow>
      <mrow>\log_{12} 144 \amp= y \;\;\text{implies}\;\;12^y = 144 \amp\text{rewrite given logarithm as an exponential}</mrow>
      <mrow>\log_{12} 144 \amp= 2 \;\;\amp y \;\text{must be equal to}\;\;2\;\;\text{for the equation to be true}</mrow>
    </md>
</example>

 </hint>
  

<!--*********************************************
            Solution
**********************************************-->
<solution>
<p>Rewrite the logarithmic expression as an exponential:
  <md>
      <mrow>\log_a x \amp= y \;\;\text{implies}\;\;a^y = x \;\;\;(\text{general definition})</mrow>
      <mrow>\log_{$a} $c{simplify} \amp= y \;\;\text{implies}\;\;$a^y = $c{simplify} \;\;\;(\text{rewrite given logarithm as an exponential})</mrow>
      <mrow>\log_{$a} $c{simplify} \amp= $b,\;\;\; (y \;\text{must be equal to}\;$b\;\;\text{for the equation to be true})</mrow>
    </md>
</p>
    
</solution>
</problem>


